# Security primitives — non-negotiable patterns

These rules are enforced by mutation testing (`stryker.config.mjs`,
threshold 84%). Any PR that weakens a primitive will surface in
`.github/workflows/mutation-test.yml`.

## Crypto

- **PII encryption** uses `encrypt()` / `decrypt()` from `lib/crypto.ts`.
  - AES-256-GCM, 12-byte IV, 16-byte auth tag.
  - Key is 64 hex chars in `ENCRYPTION_KEY`. Reject anything else.
  - Searchable fields index the HMAC (`lib/security/hmac.ts`), not the ciphertext.
- **Never log the plaintext** inside the `decrypt` catch block — only
  metadata (op, keyId, hasTag). Stryker tests enforce this.

## HMAC & constant-time

- Use `constantTimeEqual()` from `lib/security/hmac.ts` for any
  comparison that touches user-controlled secrets (webhook sig, CSRF,
  reset tokens). Never `===`.
- Hex validation strips a `sha256=` prefix **only at the start** —
  never substring match.

## CSRF

- `__Host-csrf` cookie is **intentionally** non-HttpOnly (JS reads it
  for double-submit). Do NOT "fix" this — it carries no auth material.
- `verifyDoubleSubmit()` must treat missing-cookie and missing-header
  symmetrically; otherwise attackers can distinguish states.
- Mutation-state protection only runs when `enforceDoubleSubmit=true`.

## CSP

- CSP is emitted per-request by `middleware.ts` using a fresh nonce.
  Do NOT also set it in `next.config.ts` headers (duplicate → brittle).
- `script-src` must use `'nonce-…' 'strict-dynamic'`. Never add
  `'unsafe-inline'`. The `https: http:` fallback is for pre-
  `strict-dynamic` browsers only; modern browsers ignore it.
- Every CSP change requires running `gh workflow run zap-baseline.yml`
  to confirm headers still arrive at the edge.

## Open-redirect defense

- Every `?next=…` / `redirect_to=…` param MUST go through
  `safeNextPath()` from `lib/security/safe-redirect.ts`.
- Reject paths > 1024 chars (boundary: exactly 1024 passes).
- Strip control chars + require same-origin coercion.

## Rate limiting

- All mutating endpoints must go through the Upstash Redis limiter
  (`lib/rate-limit.ts`). Fallback in-memory exists but logs a warning
  — never accept the warning as permanent state.

## Anti-patterns to reject on review

```ts
// ❌ Direct comparison of signatures
if (signature === expected) { ... }

// ✅ Constant-time
if (constantTimeEqual(signature, expected)) { ... }

// ❌ Logging decrypted value
try { return decrypt(cipher) } catch (e) { logger.error('decrypt', { cipher, e }) }

// ✅ Log metadata only
try { return decrypt(cipher) } catch (e) { logger.error('decrypt failed', { op: 'decrypt', hasTag: !!cipher.tag }) }

// ❌ Trusting next param
router.push(searchParams.get('next'))

// ✅ Coerce to safe path
router.push(safeNextPath(searchParams.get('next')))
```
